<H3> <TI>   UK Confirms Withdrawal of Troops From Belize </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0101002894 Paris AFP in Spanish 1805 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> PA0101002894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Guatemala City</LOCATION>, 31 Dec (AFP) -- The <ORGANIZATION>UK Embassy</ORGANIZATION> in 
<LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> today confirmed that the <ORGANIZATION>Belizean Government</ORGANIZATION> will 
assume responsibility for its own defense as of 1 <DATE>January 1994</DATE>, 
and announced that it had started the "immediate" withdrawal of 
the UK troops stationed in that country located in the Central 
American isthmus. 
  <PERSON>Lourdes Taylor</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>UK Embassy</ORGANIZATION>'s cultural attache, asserted 
that the process will be completed by <DATE>September 1994</DATE>. She 
added, however, that a small UK military detachment would remain 
in <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> to operate a jungle training installation. "This 
action (the troop withdrawal) reflects the <ORGANIZATION>UK Government</ORGANIZATION>'s trust 
in the much-improved relations between <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> and 
the determination of the governments of both countries to 
resolve their bilateral differences peacefully," <PERSON>Taylor</PERSON> asserted. 
  The official's statements alluded to <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>'s historic 
claims to Belizean territory. The tone of those claims eased 
after former Guatemalan President <PERSON>Jorge Serrano</PERSON> recognized 
Belizean independence in <DATE>1991</DATE>. 
  AFP talked on the phone to the spokesperson of Prime 
Minister 
<PERSON>Manuel Esquivel</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Belmopan</LOCATION>, and he explained that the UK troop 
withdrawal will be a gradual process, which was planned over the 
past seven months. It will be "a change of style in UK 
assistance" to <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Carlos Perdomo</PERSON>, who is <PERSON>Esquivel</PERSON>'s private 
secretary, asserted. The official added that after the 
approximately 1,800 soldiers leave Belizean territory, the <ORGANIZATION>UK</ORGANIZATION> 
will maintain 100 military advisers to operate a special 
training school and that a changing number of UK soldiers will 
come to be trained at that school. 
  Last week, Prime Minister <PERSON>Esquivel</PERSON> stated that the frequent 
raids by Guatemalan soldiers on Belizean territory could be "a 
bad sign" and indicative of a possible invasion. Guatemalan 
authorities denied this possibility. Perdomo disclosed that 
there is no "immediate" fear that the <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Army</ORGANIZATION> will take 
advantage of the UK troop withdrawal to take their demands by 
force. 
  The prime minister's statements, explained his secretary, 
were triggered by the fact that Guatemalan opposition sectors 
have insisted on disavowing all the actions taken by former 
President <PERSON>Serrano</PERSON>, including his agreements with <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, and 
declared them as unconstitutional. "If an opposition government 
sets in, it is possible that it will act differently from 
Presidents <PERSON>Serrano</PERSON> and (current President) De <PERSON>Leon Carpio</PERSON> have 
acted. This was the reason for the prime minister's 
statements," he added. 
  <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> obtained its independence from the UK in <DATE>1981</DATE>, but UK 
troops have remained on the territory as guarantors of its 
territorial integrity. <DATE>Ten years later</DATE>, when it recognized 
Belizean independence, <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> renounced a large part of its 
demands for the territory of the young nation. It, however, 
maintains its intentions to negotiate a passage to the <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> 
sea through the <ORGANIZATION>Belizean Province of Toledo</ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> already 
has access to the sea in the extreme southeastern part of its 
territory. Negotiations for the opening can only be initiated 
when the recognition of Belizean independence is ratified by a 
referendum in <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>

