<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Reasserts Territorial Claim on Belize </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1203021994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2241 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1203021994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Guatemala City</LOCATION>, 11 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- Today, the 
<ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> asserted in a letter to <ORGANIZATION>UN</ORGANIZATION> Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali that the country has signed no 
agreement establishing borders with <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, and it adds that 
<LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> maintains a territorial claim on the former British 
colony. 
  Foreign Minister <PERSON>Marithza Ruiz de Vielman</PERSON> asked the <ORGANIZATION>United 
Nations</ORGANIZATION> to inform its member states about the <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan 
Government</ORGANIZATION>'s territorial claim, which includes an area of land 
in Belizean territory and maritime areas on the <LOCATION>Caribbean Ocean</LOCATION>. 
Ruiz de <PERSON>Vielman</PERSON> said the joint declaration signed by the two 
states on 31 <DATE>July 1992</DATE> does not recognize the definition of 
their territorial and maritime limits. She recalled that 
<LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> recognized <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> as an independent state in <DATE>September 
1992</DATE> without relinquishing its claim, which dates back 150 years. 
  The diplomat's letter to <PERSON>Ghali</PERSON> emphasized that the 
government 
respects the free determination of nations and believes the 
settlement of controversies between states should be reached 
through peaceful means. She added that the <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Government</ORGANIZATION> 
is prepared to continue direct discussions with the former 
British colony to reach a definite solution to the dispute. 
  "<LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> formally rejects anything which violates its 
sovereignty, continental shelf, control of its territorial seas, 
or exclusive economic zone, both those defined in the past and 
those which may result when the dispute is settled," the text 
added. The document said <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>'s territorial sea is 12 
maritime miles (more than 18 km) wide. 
  "Until the dispute is settled, <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> cannot accept nor 
does it accept boundaries that are equidistant to states, 
adjacent coasts, or coasts that face each other if they 
negatively affect its sovereign right to 12 maritime miles," she 
emphasized. Ruiz said the government is willing to adopt control 
measures to prevent the violation of its laws and its customs, 
immigration, and health regulations. 
  She confirmed that the country's economic zone comprises an 
area beyond its territorial sea and adjacent zones, which extend 
200 maritime miles beyond the boundaries used to measure the 
width of its territorial sea. Also, the continental shelf 
extends 200 miles with exclusive sovereignty rights to exploit 
its natural resources, she said. 
  She emphasized that <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> will not recognize the 
charters 
or lists of geographic coordinates prepared by <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> until they 
reach a definite agreement that is satisfactory to the two 
parties. The foreign minister asked the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION> to inform 
its member states about <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>'s position on <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>

