dispute prevails between the two countries, a situation we hope 
will be handled cordially, he said. Regarding the 
organization of a <ORGANIZATION>Belizean Council</ORGANIZATION>, the ambassador said this is 
considered positive because it is a sign the <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan 
Government</ORGANIZATION> is prepared to begin negotiations to settle the 
dispute. 
  <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> is interested in establishing trade, cultural, 
and sports relations, not only with <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> but with all of 
<LOCATION>Central America</LOCATION>; and that is one of the reasons that prompt us 
to be prepared to negotiate what is negotiable, <PERSON>Anderson</PERSON> 
said. The ambassador also said he cannot release the names of 
the persons who make up the Belizean commission that will 
participate in the negotiations, because he does not have them. 
  He also referred to the role played by the media in the 
case, 
which is important, to establish the objective atmosphere 
necessary to settle relations between the States of <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> 
and <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>. The diplomat added that <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>'s recognition as an 
independent state by the media, and the illustration of this on 
the region's maps, will represent a great step forward. 

</TEXT>

