<H3> <TI>   Military Strengthened Against Potential Guatemalan Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2201000194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1431 GMT 20 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2201000194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>, 20 Jan (PL) -- The Belizean Armed 
Forces this year allotted <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> to strengthen its military 
so it will be prepared to defend national sovereignty, 
government sources disclosed today. 
  This announcement is related to a statement made last 
<DATE>November</DATE> by Prime Minister <PERSON>Manuel Esquivel</PERSON>, who said that the 
imminent withdrawal of British troops from this state would 
probably encourage its Guatemalan neighbors to reclaim this 
territory, a former colony of the <ORGANIZATION>United Kingdom</ORGANIZATION> until <DATE>1983</DATE>. 
  According to reports received in <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, spokesmen for the 
<ORGANIZATION>Belizean Government</ORGANIZATION> assured that the government is planning to 
gradually increase its troops in response to the withdrawal of 
the British, who defended the country until <DATE>last 31 December</DATE>. 
  The withdrawal of 1,200 men and combat equipment, including 
several squadrons of planes of various models, practically 
concluded on 1 <DATE>January 1994</DATE>. 
  According to official data, <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> has 1,000 armed men, 
while 
<LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> has an army of 30,000 soldiers. 
  A representative of the <ORGANIZATION>Armed Forces</ORGANIZATION> said the objective was 
to add 1,500 men in <DATE>1994</DATE> and attract more recruits in the 
following years, depending on the state budget, while making 
structural changes in the corps. 
  Diplomatic sources in <LOCATION>Belmopan</LOCATION> said the internal situation 
was calm, even though <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> has on previous occasions tried 
to annex the territory. 
  <PERSON>Julio Roberto Herrera</PERSON>, Guatemalan vice consul in the 
neighboring Mexican city of <LOCATION>Chetumal</LOCATION> (southern state of <ORGANIZATION>Quintana 
Roo</ORGANIZATION>), said that from the times of the administration of <PERSON>Jorge 
Serrano Elias</PERSON>, his country has ruled out a military intervention 
in <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>. 
  After pointing out that <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> has other priorities, the 
diplomat said: "We respect the sovereignty of <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, and even 
though we claimed that territory at one time, it doesn't mean we 
are planning an invasion." 

</TEXT>

