<HEAD>British Navy Vessel Confronted by Guatemalan Gunboat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Guatemalan gunboat fired a shot after a British
naval vessel refused its order to halt off the Central American
country of <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   A spokesman said the government will bring up <DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s incident
with the Guatemalan authorities, but he could not say whether a
protest would be filed.
   ``We'll have it taken up with them. What form that will take,
frankly I don't know,'' the spokesman said on condition of
anonymity. ``We'll have to talk with them first.''
   He said the <ORGANIZATION>HMS Fawn</ORGANIZATION>, an 800-ton inshore survey vessel, was in
the territorial waters of <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> when the Guatemalan gunboat ordered
it to stop.
   When the Fawn ignored the order, the gunboat fired a shot. Two
<ORGANIZATION>Royal Air Force Harrier</ORGANIZATION> jet fighters flew to the area, and the
Guatemalans agreed to withdraw their ship after telephone contact
with British authorities, said the official.
   <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, a former British colony, gained independence in <DATE>1981</DATE> but
requested British troops to remain until a territorial dispute with
neighboring <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> is resolved. About 2,000 British troops are
stationed in <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
