<HEADLINE>
FT  31 DEC 93 / Britain to start Belize pull-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GUATEMALA CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The British government said yesterday it would begin pulling its troops out
of <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> this <DATE>weekend</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Reuter</ORGANIZATION> reports from <LOCATION>Guatemala City</LOCATION>.
The <ORGANIZATION>UK</ORGANIZATION>, which announced last <DATE>May</DATE> that it would end its 45-year military
presence in the former British colony, has about 1,350 troops there. By the
end of next <DATE>September</DATE> all but 50 will be gone, the government said in a
statement issued by the British embassy in <LOCATION>Guatemala City</LOCATION>. Those remaining
will run a jungle training school for British troops.
British troops have been stationed in <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> to counter possible aggression
from <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>, which claimed the country as its own until recognising
<LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>'s sovereignty in <DATE>1991</DATE>. A border dispute continues but the British
government said the pull-out reflected confidence in improved relations
between the two countries.
</TEXT>
