<H3> <TI>   Mayor Urges Government To Counter Belizean Raids </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2302044994 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0216 GMT 23 Feb 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2302044994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <FÊP=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] <LOCATION>Guatemala City</LOCATION>, 21 Feb (NOTIMEX) -- Belizean troops 
have raided Guatemalan territory, demanding peasants from this 
country abandon their lands in the northern border areas, local 
Guatemalan authorities charged today. 
  "The soldiers gave us a 15-day deadline to fall back; or 
otherwise suffer the consequences," said <PERSON>Carlos Ovando</PERSON>, mayor of 
the Guatemalan hamlet of <LOCATION>Los Dolores</LOCATION> in northern <ORGANIZATION>Peten 
Department</ORGANIZATION>. The official told the <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Congress</ORGANIZATION> that 
Belizean soldiers threatened to kill the peasants in the area if 
they remain in the border region. Ovando asked for the 
<ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Government</ORGANIZATION>'s intervention to exercise greater control 
along the border in light of what he labeled a Belizean invasion. 
  Last year in <DATE>October</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Defense Ministry</ORGANIZATION> 
confirmed that Belizean soldiers had raided Guatemalan territory 
on several occasions; however, the <ORGANIZATION>Belizean Government</ORGANIZATION> ruled out 
an "erosion" of diplomatic relations. On 16 <DATE>February</DATE>, residents 
of the De Melchor de Mencos municipality in <LOCATION>Peten</LOCATION>, approximately 
10 km north of here, charged that soldiers from the neighboring 
nation had entered Guatemalan territory, destroying maiz and 
rice fields. 
  <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION> maintains -- since the time <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION> was a British 
colony -- a demand on this territory that gained its 
independence from the <LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION> in <DATE>1971</DATE>. 

</TEXT>

