<H3> <TI>   Guatemala's De Leon on Joint Central American Plans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guatemala's De Leon on Joint Central American Plans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1306020394 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2142 GMT 12 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1306020394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<FÊP=106> [By <PERSON>Jose Luis Castillejos</PERSON>] </F>
  [Excerpts] <LOCATION>Guatemala City</LOCATION>, 12 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- Guatemalan 
President <PERSON>Ramiro de Leon Carpio</PERSON> <DATE>today</DATE> said <ORGANIZATION>Central America</ORGANIZATION> will 
present joint proposals at the Fourth Ibero-American summit. 
The proposals will deal with sustained development, ecological 
defense, and the review of the Cuban and Haitian cases. 
  The Central American countries "are taking a joint proposal 
on the urgent need to form an alliance for sustained development 
in the region and ecological defense, which we hope the rest of 
the Ibero-American nations will join," De <PERSON>Leon Carpio</PERSON> said. 
  The president traveled to <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Costa Rica</LOCATION>, at <DATE>1430</DATE> 
[2030 
GMT] to meet with his Central American counterparts to adopt a 
united position on these topics. De Leon expressed optimism 
about the positive results of the Ibero-American Summit to be 
held in <LOCATION>Cartagena de Indias</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colombia</LOCATION>, on <DATE>14-15 June</DATE>. 
  He added that the meeting of government leaders from <LOCATION>Belize</LOCATION>, 
<LOCATION>Costa Rica</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>El Salvador</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Guatemala</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>, and 
<LOCATION>Panama</LOCATION>, which begins today and ends tomorrow in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, has 
the primary objective of establishing a "common front" for the 
defense of the region's interests. 
  <ORGANIZATION>Guatemalan Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> sources told NOTIMEX that during 
the <LOCATION>Cartagena</LOCATION> summit the presidents will sign a document on the 
importance that greater trade integration has for the 
hemisphere's economies. A diplomat indicated that during the 
Ibero-American Summit the Central American presidents want to 
meet with Colombian President <PERSON>Cesar Gaviria</PERSON> and Venezuelan 
President <PERSON>Rafael Caldera</PERSON> to discuss a free trade agreement 
between those two countries and <LOCATION>Central America</LOCATION>. [passage 
omitted] 
  De Leon also said the Central American presidents will 
propose the review of the current crises in <LOCATION>Haiti</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>. The 
Guatemalan president said that in <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>'s case, the island's 
return to the <ORGANIZATION>OAS</ORGANIZATION> must be conditioned on respect for human 
rights. 
  The president expressed concerned over the Haitian 
situation, 
indicating that the current economic blockade has been 
insufficient to restore a democratic regime and that, in 
addition, the threat of a military invasion is looming over 
<LOCATION>Haiti</LOCATION>. The violence in the Haitian capital due to the 
international sanctions against General <PERSON>Raoul Cedras</PERSON>' regime 
"greatly worries us, and we must seek effective solutions," De 
Leon added. 

</TEXT>

